    # the idea is to sort each line of the input
    # we can sort by the number of cities connected to each city, in descending order
    # and then by the number of roads connecting each city
    # but then we can keep an array that contains the counts of how many cities connected to each city
    # and then we can sort it
    # then we can just check the "first" element of the array
    # (it's the same as the number of cities)
    # if it's not zero, then we need to add it to our final list
    lines = sorted(list(map(lambda x: list(map(int, x.strip().split())), stdin.splitlines())))

    # by the way, we can sort the roads by the number of roads connecting each city
    # and then by the number of cities connected to each city
    # we can just make an array that contains the counts of how many roads connecting each city
    # and then we can sort it
    # then we can just check the "first" element of the array
    # (it's the same as the number of roads)

    roads = sorted(list(map(lambda x: list(map(int, x.strip().split())), stdin.splitlines())), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    # we can use a list of lists to store the counts of how many cities are connected to each city
    # we'll initialize it with zeros
    # then we'll loop through the lines, adding 1 to the corresponding element of the list
    # and then we'll keep going until we've gotten a nonzero value in every list
    cities = [[0 for _ in range(len(roads))] for _ in range(len(roads))]
    for i in range(len(lines)):

            cities[i][j] = cities[i][j] + onem(roads, i, j)
    
    # now we can check the first element of each list (this is the number of cities)

    final = []
